    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm stuck on a section of my dissertation. I've got a result where the p-value is 0.06. My advisor says it's \"not statistically significant,\" but there's a really clear trend in the visual data. Can you explain why we can't just call this a significant finding? Also, how much of this is just due to random noise in the sample?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06 suggests that while the trend you see is noticeable, there is still a 6% chance that you would observe this result purely by random chance, assuming your null hypothesis is true. To be \"statistically significant,\" the p-value typically needs to be below a predetermined threshold, usually 0.05. This difference between your finding and the threshold is the statistical hurdle; the clear trend in the visuals is evidence of a *tendency*, but the p-value quantifies the probability this tendency is just noise.",
