    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I get the math, but it's frustrating from a research perspective. It feels like the \"noise\" is almost an active force that prevents us from seeing the truth. If I have a sample size that's just slightly too small, it's like the signal gets swallowed up by those random fluctuations. Is there any way to characterize that \"chaos\" or variability more precisely, or is it just something we have to accept as an uncontrollable part of the data?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You've hit on a core frustration in empirical research; the \"noise\" is indeed the unavoidable reality of sampling from a complex system. To characterize this variability more precisely, you look at measures like the standard deviation or the standard error of the mean. These metrics quantify the typical distance of your individual data points from the average, giving you a concrete number for the expected random spread. While you cannot eliminate noise entirely, increasing your sample size is the most established way to reduce its *influence* on your test results, allowing the true signal to emerge more clearly.",
      "source": "target",
